<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1089,302,550]" box="[113,625,302,326]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,251,302,326]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">Description.</emphasis>
Body length of 
<typeStatus box="[423,516,302,326]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity box="[523,621,302,326]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.6" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="6.6">6.60 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1089,302,550]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">Male: Body flattened, parallel, densely pubescent, dull. Head yellow, vertex with large black spot not touching inner margin of eyes, mandibles with darkened apices. Pronotum yellow with three black spots (one median and two lateral). Scutellum black, elytra metallic green. Underside yellow. Legs yellow, outer margin of tibiae darkened, last two tarsomeres infuscate. Antennae yellow, all segments with slightly darkened apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1089,302,550]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">Labrum transverse, laterally covered with several pale setae, anterior margin sinuate. Anterior part of head semiopaque, sparsely covered with long pale setae. Space between anten- nae with small groove. Frontal tubercles small, subtriangular, transverse, semiopaque. Vertex dull, coarsely and densely punctate, covered with short pale hairs. Antennae filiform, 0.85 times as long as body, length ratio of antennomeres 1 to 11 equal to 22-10-20-28-24-23-22- 20-18-18-20.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174152" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5174152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174152/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" startId="13.[113,152,1535,1554]" targetBox="[242,955,597,1504]" targetPageId="13">
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1090,1535,1581]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">
Figs. 23-24. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[224,375,1535,1554]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oborili" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[224,375,1535,1554]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="78">Apophylia oborili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[383,451,1535,1554]" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
23 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 24 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Pronotum tranverse, 1. 75 times as broad as long, widest at anterior third, narrowed anteriad and posteriad, dull, densely covered with coarse punctures and pale hairs. Surface with feebly impressed median line and two large deep lateral depressions. Anterior margin concave, posterior margin almost straight. Anterior and posterior margins thinly bordered, lateral margins indistinctly bordered. Anterior angles widely rounded with distinct tooth, posterior angles obtusely angulate; all angles bearing one long pale seta.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Scutellum subtriangular with widely rounded apex, semiopaque with small dense punctures and short pale hairs. Elytra parallel and dull. Humeral calli well developed. Elytral surface covered with small and very dense, confluent punctures and short pale hairs. Epipleura distinct but narrow, disappearing before apex. Macropterous.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Ventral surface semiopaque to lustrous, finely punctate and covered with pale hairs. Last visible ventrite with deep subtrapezoidal incision.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
Tarsomere 1 of hind legs robust, as long as two following tarsomeres combined (
<figureCitation box="[1033,1112,735,759]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="13.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-128@13.[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs. 23-24. Apophylia oborili sp. nov. 23 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 24 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174152/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Claws bifid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" box="[182,524,799,823]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
Shape of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[442,521,799,823]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="13.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-128@13.[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs. 23-24. Apophylia oborili sp. nov. 23 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 24 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174152/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" box="[182,371,831,855]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1125,223,1079]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,402,863,887]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Owing to the robust aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[753,858,863,887]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oborili" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[753,858,863,887]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">A. oborili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[867,952,864,887]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neavei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">A. neavei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[228,311,896,919]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
However, the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[601,703,895,919]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oborili" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[601,703,895,919]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">A. oborili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[711,794,896,919]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is more slender in lateral view and not as wide in the apical part (
<figureCitation box="[516,599,927,951]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="12.[151,190,1121,1140]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1083]" captionTargetId="figure-119@12.[185,1092,220,1083]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs. 20-22. Apophylia neavei sp. nov. 20 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 21 – last ventrite of female; 22 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174150/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Figs 20</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[610,640,927,951]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="13.[113,152,1535,1554]" captionTargetBox="[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-128@13.[242,955,597,1504]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs. 23-24. Apophylia oborili sp. nov. 23 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 24 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174152/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
